Crimea and Sudetenland, a similar struggle ?
BRUSSELS – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has known since the Nazi Germany's annexation of the Sudetenland in 1938.
It is certainly common today to downplay the significance of the "lessons of Munich" when referencing this episode, in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier acquiesced to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
However, if the West were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of an invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the seizure of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might deeply regret their inaction.
In Western capitals, reactions have thus far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – an expulsion from the G8, for instance – would likely seem amusing if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin views the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most grave catastrophe of the modern era, the man striving tirelessly to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin displays.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have cost him almost nothing so far.
His initiative in favor of a Eurasian Economic Community has allowed him to rally a certain number of energy-rich states to Russia, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
The Armenian government, under Russian pressure, has rejected the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most prized geostrategic trophy - Ukraine - that could well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a suborned and subordinated Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the overwhelming majority of Ukrainians aspire to nothing more than joining neither the Russian nor the Soviet empires, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now be a highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union minus a Communist Party.
If the international community wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with a determination commensurate to the degree of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for commercial agreements, and other participation in forums as unproductive as the G8 will not be enough.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let's recall, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope that the Kremlin will abandon its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could it be?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles to Russian traffic, as it did after the 2008 Russian-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the US.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading to Russian ports on the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military pretensions – would be substantial.
Turkey is allowed to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus turn the argument invoked by Putin to justify the seizure of Crimea - that he would preserve the Russian ethnic groups living there - on its head by claiming it is protecting its own Turkish relatives of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a U-turn in mid-air, to head towards Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not tender himself, could thus follow in Putin's footsteps by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian traffic – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event Russia sought to intimidate it.
Secondly, American President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran over its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, denying access to the US financial system for all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would allow for an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the first years of the post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist approach could come at a steep price for them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true drama in the eyes of Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union presented China with the most formidable geostrategic windfall imaginable.
In an instant, this empire that had ravaged millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished into thin air.
Since the historical translation of "Chine" is "China", and the translations of the preceding sentences are consistent with the summaries, style, and tone, the translated sentence would be:
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously displeased China, as seen at the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit held after the war, which brought together a number of ex-Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland.
The Russian Federation has attempted to persuade the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation to recognise the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organisation has however expressed its disagreement.
Now, the countries of Central Asia – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have risen against the Kremlin without China's backing.
It now falls to President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's bold moves.
The true test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed be played out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other possible sanctions are also being considered.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas refused or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a certain number of assets, including those laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It's only when the pain becomes unbearable, and especially for the elite, that this sort of kampf led by Putin today will ultimately fail.
The price of inaction might be substantial.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this promise of America to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
When Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the explicit condition that the US (alongside the UK, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea remains annexed, no one will be able to blame Ukraine if it decides to rearm its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him using the famous phrase "You had the choice between war and dishonor."
"You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are facing a similar choice today.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will ultimately serve them a new war.
